        <prj:TechnicalJustification>
            <prj:justificationText>Imaging:
NGC3351 has a predicted SMBH mass M_BH~1.5x10^7 M_sun from its stellar velocity dispersion measurement sigma_V~120 km/s (Ho et al. 2009; Gultekin et al. 2009), and thus a well-constrained SMBH sphere of influence. As shown in Figures 3-4, well resolving the SMBH sphere of influence significantly increases the accuracy of the SMBH mass measurement. We thus propose to map NGC3351 in the CO(3-2) line (Band 7), for which the flux can be estimated. Using the extended array configuration C34-6, this yields a synthesised beam of ~0.16", enough to clearly separate the SMBH kinematic signature from that of the bulk of the stars given a good velocity resolution and signal-to-noise ratio (see Figs. 3-4).

The largest angular scale visible in this array configuration is ~2.6", smaller than the total extent of the molecular disk (see Fig. 2), but much larger than the region we must image near the SMBH (Figs. 3-4). Experience shows that central molecular disks like the one targeted here are composed of individual GMCs with typical sizes of 15-90 pc at CO(1-0) (Bolatto et al. 2008), or 0.3-1.9" at our adopted distance of 10 Mpc (NED; slightly smaller at higher frequencies). It is thus possible that we will resolve out some flux, and we conservatively allow a factor of 3 for this in our flux estimate below.

To show that the requested data will fulfil our science goals, we created mock observations of NGC3351 using our simulation tools (Davis et al. 2013a, b), the total circular velocity curve of Figure 3, and the CO surface brightness profile derived from current observations (Fig. 2). These were then input into the CASA ALMA simulator, and the results are shown in Figure 4. The uv coverage and image quality are excellent despite the minimum integration time (see below), and most importantly the kinematic signature of the SMBH is clearly detected, demonstrating that our proposed observations and analysis methods are sound.

Correlator:
We request a frequency set-up allowing us to cover the CO(3-2) line with a 1875 MHz baseband (1630 km/s) and a raw spectral resolution of 0.976 MHz (~0.85 km/s). This covers the entire velocity width expected, including any high-velocity gas detected around the SMBH. From Figures 3-4, it is clear that the higher the spectral resolution, the better the SMBH mass determination (at fixed signal-to-noise ratio S/N). We thus aim here to ultimately have 5 km/s channels (matching the expected SMBH signature shown in Figs. 3-4), although the final binning will be adjusted based on the exact source brightness at small radii, to reach an optimal compromise between spectral resolution and S/N (minimising the uncertainty on the SMBH mass).

We include three continuum spectral windows to measure and remove any continuum emission present.

Sensitivity:
NGC3351 has a CO(1-0) integrated flux of ~1513 Jy  km/s with a velocity width of 280 km/s (Helfer et al. 2003), thus an average flux of ~7.9 Jy at CO(3-2) given the CO(3-2)/CO(1-0) ratio of ~4.4 measured by Tan et al. (2013) and assuming 66% resolved out flux. Experience shows that the emission is normally only spatially resolved in one direction (tracing the ``spider'' diagram) in individual velocity channels. We thus take the number of synthesised beams across the source in each channel as the ratio of the minor-axis length (~15"; see Fig. 2) to the synthesised beam size (0.16"). We therefore expect to have ~90 beams per channel across the entire source, leading us to request a rms flux of ~8.5 mJy/beam to reach S/N=10 per synthesised beam in each channel within the region imaged (sufficient given the SMBH signature, see Figs. 3-4). The ALMA Observing Tool suggests that reaching this limits at 345 GHz with the default 0.658 mm PWV, C34-6 array configuration, and 5 km/s channels will only require the minimum ~2 min on-source, or ~0.5 hr including all calibrations and overheads.</prj:justificationText>
        </prj:TechnicalJustification>
